---
description: Enforce thin route handlers and service-layer business logic
globs: src/server/lib/routes/**/*.ts
alwaysApply: true
---

# Handler-Service Boundary Rule

Use this rule whenever implementing or modifying route handlers.

## Handler responsibilities (allowed)

Handlers may:

- read validated request inputs (`c.req.valid(...)`)
- read auth/context (`jwtPayload`, bindings, request metadata)
- call service methods
- map service results/errors to HTTP response shape/status

### Valid

```ts
export const patchProfileHandler: RouteHandler<...> = async (c) => {
  const input = c.req.valid('json');
  const userId = c.get('jwtPayload').sub;
  const result = await profileService.updateProfile(c.env, userId, input);
  return c.json(result, 200);
};
```

## Handler responsibilities (disallowed)

Handlers must not:

- contain business workflows beyond trivial orchestration
- call third-party SDKs directly (Auth0, email providers, LiveKit, etc.)
- duplicate logic that belongs in domain services
- embed repository/DB query logic directly

### Invalid

```ts
export const patchProfileHandler = async (c) => {
  const mgmt = new ManagementClient(...); // provider SDK in handler
  const db = drizzle(c.env.DB); // DB logic in handler
  // business logic and external calls mixed here
};
```

## Service boundary

Business logic and provider integration must live in:

- `src/server/lib/services/**`

Services should:

- expose typed input/output contracts
- expose typed domain errors (or discriminated result types)
- avoid leaking provider-specific raw errors to handlers

### Valid

```ts
export type UpdateProfileResult =
  | { ok: true; givenName: string; familyName: string }
  | { ok: false; code: 'NOT_FOUND' | 'UPSTREAM_ERROR'; message: string };
```

### Invalid

```ts
export async function updateProfile(...) {
  // throws provider-native error objects directly to route handlers
}
```
